              </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">The Political Weather</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <p>
              The 1960s across Asia were years of postcolonial re-shaping, Cold War influences, and new national identities being formed. Music was often both entertainment and cultural weapon.</p>
              <!-- sub sections -->
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              India & Pakistan were navigating independence legacies — music was a bridge between modernity and tradition.
                Japan was experiencing a post-war boom that fueled Western cultural imports alongside avant-garde experiments.
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
                China under the Cultural Revolution (1966 onward) largely suppressed popular and traditional music in favor of revolutionary songs.
              </div>
              <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
                Taiwan, Philippines, Thailand, and Indonesia were balancing Western cultural inflows (especially American rock ‘n’ roll and surf) with local traditions.            </p>
              </div>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- What People Were Hearing -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/10 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9 19V6l12-3v13M9 19c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zm12-3c0 1.105-1.343 2-3 2s-3-.895-3-2 1.343-2 3-2 3 .895 3 2zM9 10l12-3"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">What People Were Hearing</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            Before the flood of Western rock sounds, Asian countries had deeply rooted traditions that shaped how they absorbed the 60s:
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              India: Hindustani & Carnatic classical, bhajans, folk traditions, and an already flourishing film music industry.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Pakistan: Ghazals, qawwalis, and folk forms like Sindhi and Punjabi songs.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              Sri Lanka: Kandyan drumming, Baila (Afro-Portuguese influenced), and Buddhist devotional music.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Japan: Enka (sentimental ballads rooted in folk) dominated pre-60s.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              China: Traditional Chinese opera and revolutionary anthems.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Taiwan, Philippines, Thailand, Indonesia: Local folk and ritual music, gamelan (Indonesia), kulintang (Philippines), and luk thung (Thailand).
            </div>
          </div>

          
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- What you can find in this playlist -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/10 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M13 10V3L4 14h7v7l9-11h-7z"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">What you can find in this playlist            </h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-6">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4"> 
              Asian Psych Rock: By the late 60s, places like Indonesia birthed bands such as The Steps and Koes Plus, blending fuzz guitars with gamelan sensibilities.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Philippines Manila Sound & Garage: Teen bands covered Beatles/Stones with Tagalog inflections; later influencing Manila Sound.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              Japanese Group Sounds (GS): Rock bands like The Spiders emerged, absorbing surf and garage but in Japanese lyrical styles.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              India’s Film Experiments: Bollywood composers (R.D. Burman, S.D. Burman) mixed jazz, funk, and Hindustani melodies. Tamil, Telugu, and Malayalam composers (M.S. Viswanathan, Ilaiyaraaja emerging later) fused Carnatic ragas with rock instrumentation.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              Sri Lanka Baila Fusion: Took African-Portuguese rhythms and blended them into catchy, dancey pop.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Pakistan: Vital qawwalis from Nusrat Fateh Ali Khan’s family line and pop experiments by Ahmed Rushdi (who pioneered early Pakistani pop).
            </div>

           
          </div>

        </div>
      </div>


      <!-- The Tech Factor -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/10 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M9.75 17L9 20l-1 1h8l-1-1-.75-3M3 13h18M5 17h14a2 2 0 002-2V5a2 2 0 00-2-2H5a2 2 0 00-2 2v10a2 2 0 002 2z"></path>
            </svg>
            <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">Technological changes </h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="text-lg leading-relaxed text-[#064161] space-y-4">
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              India: Harmonium, tabla, sitar, mridangam + electric guitar, organ, and Western brass began to dominate in film orchestration.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              South India: Carnatic compositions incorporated violin, veena, mridangam alongside jazz drum kits and electronic keyboards (later).
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              Pakistan/Sri Lanka: Harmonium, dholak, bansuri, sitar paired with electric guitar, bass, and drum kits in film and radio orchestras.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              Japan: Imported Fenders and Mosrite guitars drove garage/GS bands.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#FEE96A] pl-4">
              Indonesia & Philippines: Surf guitars, Farfisa organs, fuzz pedals alongside local percussion.
            </div>
            <div class="border-l-4 border-[#C13870] pl-4">
              China: Revolutionary ensembles often used traditional instruments (erhu, pipa) in large propagandistic orchestras.
            </div>
          </div>


            </div>  
          </div>
            
          
        </div>
      </div>

      <!-- Notable Artists -->
      <div class="accordion-item bg-white border border-[#FEE96A]/30 rounded-lg overflow-hidden">
        <button class="accordion-trigger w-full px-6 py-4 text-left bg-[#FEE96A]/10 hover:bg-[#FEE96A]/20 transition-colors flex justify-between items-center">
          <div class="flex items-center space-x-3">
            <svg class="w-6 h-6 text-[#064161]" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
              <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M16 7a4 4 0 11-8 0 4 4 0 018 0zM12 14a7 7 0 00-7 7h14a7 7 0 00-7-7z"></path>
            </svg>
              <h4 class="text-xl text-[#064161]">Notable Artists</h4>
          </div>
          <svg class="accordion-icon w-5 h-5 text-[#064161] transform transition-transform" fill="none" stroke="currentColor" viewBox="0 0 24 24">
            <path stroke-linecap="round" stroke-linejoin="round" stroke-width="2" d="M19 9l-7 7-7-7"></path>
          </svg>
        </button>
        <div class="accordion-content hidden px-6 py-4">
          <div class="space-y-6">
            {data.notable_artists.map((region, index) => (
              <div>
                <h5 class={`text-lg font-bold text-[#064161] mb-4 border-b-2  pb-2 ${index%2==0? 'border-[#FEE96A]' : 'border-[#C13870]'}`}>{region.title}</h5>
                <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 lg:grid-cols-3 gap-4">
                  {region.artists.map((artist) => (
                    <div class={`${index%3==0? 'bg-[#FEE96A]/10' : 'bg-[#C13870]/10'} p-4 rounded-lg border border-[#C13870]/30`}>
                     
                      {artist.image && <img src={artist.image} alt={artist.name} class="w-24 h-24 rounded-full object-cover">}
                      <h6 class="font-bold text-[#064161]">{artist.name}</h6>
                      <p class="text-sm text-[#064161]/80">{artist.description}</p>
                    </div>
                  ))}
                </div>
              </div>
            ))}
              </div>
            
          
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>


</div>

<script>
  // Accordion functionality
  document.addEventListener('DOMContentLoaded', () => {
    const accordionTriggers = document.querySelectorAll('.accordion-trigger');
    
    accordionTriggers.forEach(trigger => {
      trigger.addEventListener('click', () => {
        const accordionItem = trigger.closest('.accordion-item');
        const content = accordionItem?.querySelector('.accordion-content');
        const icon = trigger.querySelector('.accordion-icon');
        
        if (content && icon) {
          const isOpen = !content.classList.contains('hidden');
          

          
          // Toggle current accordion
          if (isOpen) {
            content.classList.add('hidden');
            icon.classList.remove('rotate-180');
          } else {
            content.classList.remove('hidden');
            icon.classList.add('rotate-180');
          }
        }
      });
    });
  });
</script>


